He governed Libya as Revolutionary Chairman of the <a12_0>Libyan Arab Republic<a12_0/> from <a8_0>1969<a8_0/> to 1977 and then as the "<a13_0>Brotherly Leader<a13_0/>" of <a4_0>the Great Socialist People's Libyan Arab Jamahiriya <a5_0>from 1977 to 2011<a5_0/><a4_0/>. <a1_0>Initially ideologically committed to Arab nationalism and Arab socialism<a1_0/>, he came to rule according to <a2_0>his own <a9_0>Third International Theory<a9_0/><a2_0/> before embracing <a3_0><a6_0>Pan-Africanism<a6_0/><a3_0/> and serving as Chairperson of the African Union from 2009 to 2010.
